The Prague Stock Exchange went down at the end of the trade
The Prague stock exchange corrected its losses after the early morning crash.
Transactions with the shares of the Czech Energy Enterprise (ČEZ) accounted for almost half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague stock market continued its fall on Monday after the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by six percent.
This time, the fall of Wall Street stocks is behind the fall.
This is also reflected in the market reaction to the result of a vote by the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to support the financial sector’s stabilization plan.
Shares in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although the indicators eventually canceled some of the losses during the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng stock index dropped four percent during trading, but later canceled some of the losses and reduced the drop to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai closed.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange fell 3.6 percent according to the Taiwan Stock Exchange Index.
“The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and will affect the global financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it determines its monetary policy independently of the Chinese central bank.
In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should immediately resume negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Other countries are threatened to suffer the consequences.
The Bloodshed of American Shares
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a bill to support the financial system, which would have cost $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
Thus, lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
Bush said the bill would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloodshed and leading stock indices recorded the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell 7 percent, the last time it experienced a similar drop was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal was not accepted in the House of Representatives, the index began to drop.
Congress Resigns: U.S. Government Could Pump $700 Billion into Banks
The top leaders of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on the broader form of the agreement and on financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve a bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion ($12 trillion) financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
There is no victory yet.
Congress must complete some details of the agreement before it can publish the final form of the law and its vote.
The draft budget will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
This was announced by Barney Frank, chairman of the Committee on Financial Organizations.
Senate sources say they are likely to vote on the bill as early as Wednesday.
Economists say there should be an announcement of the approval of the bailout plan, which is the first important psychological factor in the recovery of the financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, there is a "outbreak" thereafter.
The plan must be effective.
“We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our divergent views on what the package should be like to stabilize the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
The final vote may take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Saturday night to give a final form to the government fund.
This would involve the purchase of non-selling mortgage assets from financial companies, which would cause financial firms to suffer severe losses and jeopardize the stability of the entire system.
“We are close to a final agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The repair plan still needs to continue, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal to Asian Trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Senator Harry Reid, a Democrat from Nevada, said lawmakers are seeking a deal in Congress on Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors before trading begins in Asian financial markets, where the time zone could be the first to influence Monday’s Congressional decision.
It is unclear when the two houses of the U.S. Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether the trial will be stopped at the last minute due to a problem.
Legislators hope that the law will be passed in the coming days.
However, the law is undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
According to President George W. Bush, the first $350 billion should be made available as soon as possible.
However, Congress may block the issue of the remaining amount, which was set to be another $100 billion and subsequently $350 billion, if it feels that the program is not performing its function.
Bush assesses progress in negotiations
Although the President may veto this decision, Congress may override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was the acquisition of assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that lost their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay off their mortgages.
“We have prepared everything.
The law should be able to be voted by the House of Representatives on Sunday and by the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President Bush is pleased with the progress made.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was pleased with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “the bilateral efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of end-of-life compensation
Christopher Dodd, the chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, who led the negotiations, said lawmakers had agreed on the responsibility for the financial program, on protecting taxpayers from losses, on closing the discounts, and on timing the funding draft.
The new law also limits the so-called bounty compensation of directors participating in the program and establishes a supervisory committee for the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and have made great progress towards a deal that will work and benefit all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also counts on helping homeowners who have trouble with repayment.
The government should negotiate new payments for the mortgages it purchases, with the aim of reducing the monthly payments of debtors and enabling them to keep their homes.
Spiritual aid
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"All this is because it is not possible to know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and government will distribute the losses,” Marek told the iHNed.cz website this week.
Marek said it is not so important whether the plan will be approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“More importantly, Congress will decide this week whether they will support the plan and give their blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of agreeing that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment," Marek said.
MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We help you choose
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, you can’t make phone calls with any MP3 player.
It seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
There are many reasons why you should buy an MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the future owner.
You will probably find it difficult to get a high-quality, expensive record player for your home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulence record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on bakelite discs, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality.
However, if your shelves are filled with art rock, jazz or blues bakelets, you’re probably dreaming of such a record player.
This is similar to travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will probably find it difficult to accept a 20 crowns market earphone.
There are two extremes between which everyone has enough space.
The choice is wide.
The lifetime of the elements also matters.
Some top-notch music players can do much more than just playing music, but also what most mobile phones don’t even happen to.
No device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary features, calling and texting, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera in it, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a little wonder, as no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
Many mobile phones also have disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more times the display will send it to the charger.
Music is one of the greatest energy sources.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobile phones, therefore, expect that they will not play for you for more than a few hours.
If you’re still calling here and there, bring an additional charger to your workplace for safety reasons – this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have such a problem, even the worst will withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to your mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without specialized software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can cope with miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod) players do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library ordered based on the artist, the album, the genre name, or, for example, the user's evaluation.
Some devices only display a wooden structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with an operating system).
Players are easier to manage, mobile phones know more
When choosing a particular device, you should first consider the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output, and, of course, the convenience of handling.
If your music is primarily used as a background and you only listen to it for a short period of time every day, for example on the radio, any MP3 player is suitable for you.
Any mobile phone can do this.
You do not even have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player can.
With MP3, everyone will cope, and the vast majority of the music that reaches you will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most widely used formats, and the vast majority of devices also handle WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow for online music purchases, for example.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the provider (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service itself can be a strong argument for purchasing mobile music.
Unfortunately, the offer of providers is vague and is generally limited to one-year radio loads only.
Prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them all the time.
Whenever he wants to listen to something, he holds his cell phone in his pocket while the forgotten MP3 player lies at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your earphones or at least your loudspeakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile, but only a few MP3 players have.
For many, the biggest advantage of mobile phones will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can already get a pretty decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of a traditional earphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns with conventional 3.5mm hole earphones.
The main advantage of these devices is, among other things, the ease of handling.
The easiest - not necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) are really everybody can cope with.
Minimum functionality, comparable to previously conventional cassette magneto or gramofon handling is obvious.
There is no threat of collapse in the form of accidentally connected mobile internet, nor in the case of the subsequent huge bill for data transmission.
What Equipment to Choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
You can also purchase the right card for a maximum of 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive can start with up to 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not need to spend more than 1,100 SEK.
If you belong to the more demanding students, prefer to choose specialized mobile walkers (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, which makes it convenient to access your MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson is the leader in the industry, with its Walkman series phones having the same user interface as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above-mentioned brands can offer the same service in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our providers offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here for us - a virtual provider that forces classic providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won’t be that long anymore.
On the Mobil.cz website we have written many times that the Czech providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ, which pointed to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the recent step of the European Commission to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - SMS sent from abroad to some customers of Czech mobile operators will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is no real competition.
This may sound controversial as we also have three mobile networks and our penetration is high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are pleased to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, has repeatedly stated that there is no place for a new provider in the Czech Republic.
Per it’s true that a classic provider with its own network probably won’t have a lot of chances (although it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is another option - the virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that brought a significant price drop, to which classical providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before the big fish markets, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in the UK, heard sounds similar to ours.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can really be successful.
However, we do not need to go too far for an example.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider managed to gain more than 100,000 customers in just six months and became the fifth largest provider there.
In the meantime, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is the ability to focus on a much smaller target group.
In order to operate efficiently, it requires far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual providers in the world thus tend to appear as low-cost – they offer cheap calls and text messages, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers at least 50 percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good move to bet on a target group.
This service is specifically aimed at men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual provider.
It’s hard to say if a similar idea can also work in Poland.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesman, doubts about this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of service offerings.”
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators claim to be unlikely
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but the talks in the Czech Republic do not seem to be too hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not excessively sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their utmost to prevent any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has not hidden its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider for a while, which thus aims to take another step in making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in offering our customers not only wireless, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile providers.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, the group’s spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
From unofficial information, it seems that we may be lucky with the first virtual provider by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this point, we do not think that a full-value virtual provider would have a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market is very special, unlike other markets.
Until now, we have not been called by a single entity offering a complex and serious project in this area,” said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefónica 02.
Other service providers also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile spokeswoman, exceptionally agrees with O2 and adds: “So far we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects that could be further based on.”
And he added: “It is unlikely that any virtual provider will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, there should be a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, primarily in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable for customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find partners to build shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - in line with service providers
The behavior of mobile operators is easily understood, the entry of another operator would increase competition, lead to price decreases and thus their profits decrease.
So why facilitate entering such a competition?
When the service providers are able to collaborate on something important, there is also a whirlwind around the birth of U:fon.
The biggest pressure on ČTÚ was probably around the birth of T-Mobile’s U:phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the website.
But now it is U:fon that comes as a good argument for why we do not allow the entrance of the virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová added: “The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been affected by the fourth mobile operator’s access to the market.
Given the nature of the Czech mobile market, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services would pose high demands.”
However, given this attitude of mobile operators, the Czech regulatory authorities are completely uninterested.
Meanwhile, it is not just about the ČTÚ’s attitude, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic – unlike the UK and other developed countries – has no right to interfere in economic competition.
Only the competition authority has the right to do so.
But the office is characteristic of the whole problem.
“The entry of a virtual provider into the mobile market would only be possible after a contract between the mobile provider and the virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure was concluded.
So far, no such agreement has been concluded, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting to traditional providers,” said Kristián Chlapua, of the Department of External Relations of the Competition Office.
A statement from representatives of service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the agency, which should represent the interests of consumers and ensure that no one abuses its market position, this is more than strange.
Especially, if Kristián Chalupa adds, "In foreign countries, where virtual providers generally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the decline in the price of mobile phone services."
However, it is likely that the UOHS is not in the interests of pressure to ensure the proper functioning of the market environment and to lower prices.
In this case, it is really shocking to see the reaction of the three mobile providers.
The question of whether this is just a coincidence is obvious.
As with gas stations, the exact same gasoline prices are just the work of chance and fierce competition.
“The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers have a leading position, i.e. they have no proportionate responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership position is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, based on which telecommunications is the only market in terms of economic competition.
After that, of course, there is no Czech service provider in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the establishment of a virtual provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment it is necessarily dominant.
But even if this argument is not accepted, it should be a minimum warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting remarkably similarly.
Meanwhile, complaints from a number of stakeholders (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they face very similar obstacles in negotiating with all providers.
The imposition of responsibility on ČTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the ÚOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have already encountered it in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of the ČTÚ’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not implemented, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
This should be well understood by the representatives of the UOHS, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is watching.
Meanwhile, the operation of some kind of fake virtual service providers remains unnoticed, many of which are already operating on Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, which, however, are only partially public.
It is a multilevel marketing company.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Pricing lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts against the provider as a classic corporate customer ordering large amounts of SIM cards.
As a preferred customer, you will receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile providers prohibit similar pre-sales.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of contract terms that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of our cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this issue.
But it is unlikely that the news of such activity would not have reached the responsible people of the mobile providers.
These three companies have thousands of customers.
At the same time, no provider protects against such a procedure.
In fact, these companies have no negligible profits from their activities and at the same time, unlike real virtual providers, they are not threatened with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not on their name, so they can’t have it as fully as general customers of mobile operators.”
At least that’s what I should be curious about.
In addition, another question arises for the OOHS.
If mobile operators shut their eyes on a similar procedure, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual provider?
It should be added that the UOHS has a relatively strong authority to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish, it does not have to be content with explaining to the providers that they did not suspect such a thing and that their commercial terms prohibit it.
When you are the most expensive
As has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market has resulted in a noticeable decline in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually every country where virtual providers have been established, traditional providers have tried to prevent their establishment more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually the same - too small, possibly too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulatory authorities intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual provider, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies give the whole matter to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies are good for them in these cases.
But don’t give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual provider with us really appears soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one provider would allow the establishment of a virtual mobile provider, it would be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to rejecting (discriminating) further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may no longer be going to call more expensive.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to four edits of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On the National Day of the Czech Republic, Prime Minister Mirek Topolanek presented the new recordings of the national anthem of the Czech Republic.
The anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solos, with a singing arm or instrumentally.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sing.
The authors of the modification of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He told the Czech Radio earlier that he has deliberately chosen young singers with representative voices that are expressive and popular to sing the vocal variations.
“From the very beginning, I have been working with both of them, and later with the band, to ensure clear diction, clear text and consistency,” he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song “Where is my homeland?” was first performed in the Rendi Theater in 1834 in Josef Kajetán’s play “Tyl Fidlovačka”, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously regarded it as their own.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
Even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
