The Prague transport company will deliver with a chip card for the first time on Wednesday
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the Prague Transportation Company entered its history as the first passenger to board metro, trams and buses with an electronic voucher in their pocket instead of a paper line ticket.
Currently, the coupon is available to approximately 100,000 people who have an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (valid from 1 January 2009) and save it on their chip cards at the Transportation Company’s information centers and offices at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons can be purchased online from yesterday via the Transportation Company’s website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers in the afternoon.
Those who are beginning to use online trading may forever forget about the subway stations where they had to go through long rows for line tickets.
The voucher can be purchased via the Internet and saved on an Opencard card in one of the thirteen accounts of the City Library.
“In these locations, passengers have a desk with trained servers to help those interested in online shopping and save their purchased coupons on their cards,” said Martin Opatrný, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can also be saved to OpenCard in the self-service machines installed in some halls.
How do these machines look?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket managers and passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eight," Opatrný added.
Controls the driver instead of the driver.
Managing machines that start operating tomorrow is easy.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid voucher will be saved on its own.
Electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings from tomorrow.
So by trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499 which are used primarily by residents of the Central Czech routes to travel to the capital.
“On the integrated transport trains in Prague, guides were equipped with card readers, which can also be used to determine the validity of the coupons in the zone,” explained Filip Drápal from Ropid, the organization that compiles the schedule of public transport in Prague.
In buses around the city, card readers are integrated with the driver at the box office.
At boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard in a specified place on the side of the box.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger, for example, needs to check the validity of coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver to do so," he added with Drápal.
Passengers who travel in non-city buses and will not remember when their coupon expires can go back to self-service machines that save their coupons to cards.
Information about the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
Sudans want U.S. referendum
In 1945, the Sudet Germans demanded the annexation of Šumava to the United States.
This is revealed in the letter, which is in the collection of the Scientific Library of the South of the Czech Republic.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
This was supposedly the request of a group of Sudanese Germans to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also revealed in a surviving letter from a private archive, which is now stored in the collection of the Scientific Library in the South of the Czech Republic.
The Germans of Česky Krumlov in the letter ask the U.S. President not to allow the return of the "Shumava County" to the Czech Republic, which was still occupied by Hitler under the Munich Treaty.
"We have interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure in the words that American troops will come to German territories in no way as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it is written in the letter, signing with the words "People who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia is supposed to give the Sudet Germans - in addition to the knowledge of the Czech national character - only hope for brutality, relentlessness, non-understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US president to take over Šumava's protectorate "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million people, this territory would be judged to us as a foreign country that oppresses and exaggerates the minority, and would contribute almost nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors were unable to sign was allegedly the fear of the revenge of the “Czech oppressors.”
So if the president of the United States allegedly doubts the opinion of the Germans in Shumava, it would be enough to hold a referendum in Shumava County on whether its inhabitants want to become part of the United States and want to live under the patronage of the United States.
