Even rats have emotions.
A rat or a mole escapes in the event of danger. Does this mean that he feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same when they behave like us?
In the online journal "Edge" for years, famous scientists have published their articles.
SPIEGEL ONLINE examines the answers to the question “What do you think is real without being able to prove it?” in one of its series.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we examine other species and examine the issues of perception or consciousness in general, we come to a difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult for us to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
Circuits associated with human consciousness, on the one hand, almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This wide area is more advanced in man than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other living beings.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the awareness of who we are, or the ability to plan and make decisions, it is reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals are excluded.
However, even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would be influenced by language, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness can be in the case of other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and if it cannot be analyzed by our own experience because of the special hardware, then its research puts us in serious trouble.
Most of my explanations relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals could be studied regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in the case of experiments on primate short-term memory, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this hypothesis, which was also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely on neural connections of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: Both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the formation of visualization.
What happens to these feelings?
I lead this back to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in the brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies the working memory.
Thus, emotions are closely linked to the areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
In addition to the linguistic nature, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states so that we can describe them to others in addition to ourselves.
In contrast, for example, Antonio Damasio is of the opinion that emotions originate from the simpler activities of the body-perception areas of the cerebral cortex and brain strain, just like Jaak Pankseep, who, however, is more focused on the brain strain.
Since this network hasn’t changed much over the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in the emotions that encompass the species.
I cannot deny this in theory, but I find it unproven.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fearful in rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases: How can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach is running away in the event of danger, does he also feel fear?
In my opinion, similar behavior alone is not yet evidence of the same experience.
Although neuronal comparisons can help further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but cockroaches do not have a brain.
But is the brain responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in respect of humans, how could we prove this in respect of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, and maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspiciously fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I’m researching rats’ emotional behavior rather than their emotional emotions.
In any case, there is progress in this area at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I don’t study language and consciousness, nor feelings, because I don’t know if they exist.
For others, this may seem like a short-sighted attitude, but I prefer to move forward rather than collide with a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
