A separate city, the pride and trials of the blacks
The Greater Orlando Experience Park, a few miles from everything that is shining, loud and huge, hides a quiet little town where the pride and complexity of the African American life experience is born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country, and which was the home of Zora Neale Hurston’s childhood, is now no longer as simple as she described in 1935: “a city of five lakes, three crochet tracks, 300 brown leather, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guayavas, and two schools without prison.”
Now it is a caveat.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have already attended the annual Zora Festival. The eatonville ceremony series is held in honour of Harlem Renaissance’s most famous female writer, Hurston.
Nevertheless, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction – which is also included in the Florida Guide published by the Project of Federal Writers of the Crisis – stands apart from its surroundings.
Just as independent, dignified, and closed as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that Florida’s city black people were often reluctant to share their true thoughts with white people who “know so little about us that they don’t know what they’re missing.”
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, encourages an open discussion on the racial issue, many here are distrustful of outsiders’ views.
"We are very careful about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here all his life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
“You have to tell it correctly.”
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historic model of black exhibition, but at the same time a community of 2,400 people, where poverty rates reach twice the national average.
It is partly a literary node, and partly an example of a southern, urban, black culture, sometimes despised, sometimes praised, which was created as a result of American slavery, flourishing in the shade of oak trees.
It is not surprising, therefore, that the residents here are both proud and defensive at the same time.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone here calls it Hurston).
In books written in an honest, strong dialect — such as “Mules and Men” (1935) and “Their Eyes Were Watching God” (1937) — he presented his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida Guide have transformed the city, which lies next to Road 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was both brave in life and literature as well as drumming, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then went into the more confidential spheres.
So he wrote: "Right of the road we find a modern public school, with a white edge on a brown foundation, carefullyined courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller takes care of, though he can barely write and read."
He mentioned Widow Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells all kinds of drinks and anything you might need in the temporary accommodation.”
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, re-marriage, and sex.
Obviously, Fodor's guide showed it differently.
This description did not really please everyone.
"Zora said things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls. Hurston made them immortal by quoting from the slick songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, “Some people don’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as the alien who frequently visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
The 77-year-old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston entered the city, he usually arrived without notice in a whirling Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes and in long trousers to a city where people are still proud of their dignified dress.
He fascinated most people, said Franklin, but many were phytomized.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he shrugged his chair, adding, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were no longer re-published.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with much of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in a homeless tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he previously lived.
There were no major commemorations or large public lectures in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much it enriched the world or what it left us at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's Biography, published in 2003, entitled "Wrapped in the Rainbow."
The turning point came in 1980.
Officials in Orange County wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorway linking the states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggles with racial mixing sparked hatred against the community.
"At that time, a group of white boys came over and threw people sitting on the side of the road with oranges and other things," Franklin said.
“There was a woman who died in this.
They threw a strawberry out of a car.”
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s decision to impose forced integration, stating about the decision, “Brown v. Board of Education,” that he would “offend rather than respect my race.”
Today, residents say that even though the school segregation has been positive in some ways, it has weakened the unity of the Eatonville people and undermined the self-confidence of young people.
“Black children are accustomed to being hugged – I remember this – man hugged his teacher in the morning and in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the non-profit organization Save the Eatonville Community.
"It lasted as long as students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
"We didn't embrace our white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there were cultural differences between us," Nathiri said.
However, human rights have helped the rise of many other Zora Neale Hurston – black writers, actors, and artists who have surpassed prejudice, as she did, with such cheerful self-confidence and lines like, “How can anyone deprive himself of the enjoyment of my company!
This is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker pilgrimated to Hurston's homeless tomb and began to struggle to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a prestigious Hurston biography written by Robert E. Hemenway was placed on the shelves of bookstores, putting him once again among America’s best models.
The road construction project would have started just when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time Hurston’s old neighbors saw him as a savior.
In 1988, the community began organizing a Hurston Festival to show what would ruin the county with its main road.
Thousands of fans have attended the opening event two years later, and since then many have returned to the ceremony every January.
A few years later, the county abandoned its road construction proposal.
"Because of the five-lane upgrading of the main road, the community has been revived, connected at full speed, which is a real civil pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd said, “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory over the road construction project helped change the image of the city itself.
An increasing number of people outside the city appeared, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started visiting the church here in 1993, and the locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical Register in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (naturally named after Hurston) was opened on the refurbished and embellished Kennedy Street.
Eatonville still remains Florida’s cockroach egg: it’s not just ten kilometers from downtown Orlando, but sometimes it feels like it’s a suburban sidewalk during summer rains; it’s as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
90% of the population is black.
They are still welcomed with caution by outsiders who come here in search of the story of Eatonville.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things—such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco painted by a white man and depicting black people working on the ground—are not allowed to be photographed.
In Eatonville, many people—including the confident Jones teacher who is attracted to the bright red—are afraid of being misunderstood by their separated community.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew, the pride of the hometown grew.
Especially young people are increasingly seeing Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with its problems and with everything else, neither better nor worse, as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as the other racial and ethnic groups in America.
An honest civil bond is silenced from the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work for the local government or the police, which he believes needs help.
And it seems that even the younger ones have learned to properly characterize Eatonville, such as the 11-year-old twin couple in Winter Park: Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
“Most of the people who just travel through here think this city is nothing compared to the rest,” Alondra Kenon recently said on a Sunday after the worship.
“But if you stop and take some time to learn about its history, it’s a very beautiful city.”
