"I don't take pictures on stage because I want to present the artist from a personal side" Günther Bauer Photographer
There are no hairstyles, no dancing shoes.
The great masters of flamenco are close to the body, without the excitement of acting: to get to know the ordinary faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, ordinary people.
And these two sides cannot be separated except in the intimate, distant moments from the audience, when one can take a personal move, grasp the depth of a captured gaze, or grasp the beauty of the actless, yet expressive hand of the artist who is about to perform on stage.
In the German photographic series “Flamenco-people” by Günther Bauer, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with the less-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, she shows the flamenco’s distinctive iconography from different perspectives.
The exhibition, which is part of the Month of Flamenco Photography, "reflects the growing international importance of flamenco from day to day," the creator believes, adding that the flamenco-people "should be the protagonist of anyone, since when viewing the images, the observer finds that these images do not represent artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
However, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character dwell in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture the personality of the flamenco with the help of the camera.”
The Cante de las Minas festival inspired Bauer to embark on a long journey in 1997, during which he took portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers using a disc camera.
These portraits draw back to classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of themes.
The application of various stylistic tools, however, breaks with traditional visual representation and suggests modernity.The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's vision of flamenco: "It is a music with traditional roots, which, however, changes from day to day and is always impressive."
It is not the dance, not the singing or the music in itself, but rather the artist’s personality and character that enchants the audience.
These days, the guiding motif of the works that can be viewed in the El Fotómata gallery is the search for the encounter with the essence, the artistic magic, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and presentation.
The names of famous flamenco figures, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, symbolize this collection of photographs featuring sixty artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, which will soon be covered by an album of portraits presented at the exhibition.
Bauert’s passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea two years ago with the series “Portraits of Veterans Athletes” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concept of the Flamenco-people is slightly different from this, the photographer adds: “I really like to photograph people, get to know them and get into their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult art of photography is portrait.
The fate brings you together with people you meet, with personalities you sometimes don’t even know, or who only spend a few minutes photographing.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
The flamenco-people exhibition, selected from portraits of contemporary flamenco, can be viewed at the El Fotómata Gallery at calle de la Mata 20 parallel to Alameda de Hércules until 16 October.
