Recurring drunk drivers will be obliged to install the "Alcolock"
After three violations due to drunk driving, the Ministry of the Interior would order the driver to install a mechanism that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is drunk or does not blow into the mechanism.
The proposal was submitted in June and is currently being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will last a year.
Since the project aims to re-enter traffic, the driver will also have to take a repetitive course on transport education.
In addition to the General Prosecutor’s Office for Traffic Safety, the General Directorate for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation for Automotive Safety Technology Institute (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers who have been arrested several times for drunk driving are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock because the system connected to the vehicle determines the level of alcohol in the inhaled air. If it is higher than permitted, or if the driver has not inhaled the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of more than 1,000 euros would be borne by the infringer.
A 2007 U.S. study showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, this rule is estimated to save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure focuses on violations for two reasons: on the one hand, it makes it easier to prevent them from becoming a crime.
On the other hand, it is easier to implement because the implementation of the legal reform takes place as usual, while the necessary criminal reform would require an amendment to the basic law.
The device is not yet commercially available on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and utility vehicles in a pilot mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers’ Party, which, on the French model, calls for the system to be installed in school buses.
