Those who talk in their dreams
Some children talk at night.
I don’t think of those who wake up and tell them what happened to them that day, but of those who talk while they are asleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but in reality it is completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
Some of them said they talked at night.
In terms of frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a disease accompanied by a high fever) or more regular (once a day, once a week or once a month), and usually the next day the child remembers nothing.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single triggering cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nighttime waking, nighttime sleeping (enuresis nocturna) or sleeping, but this is not legal.
As mentioned above, it can be accompanied by a condition associated with high fever, or even a stressful situation or an increased state of excitement.
So far, it has been studied very little.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, consist of unrelated words, murmuring, but contrary to all this, it can also occur in the form of screaming, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and consult a specialist.The examination can reveal whether there is a problem that causes great anxiety in the background and thus can offer a solution.
As mentioned above, it is a benign phenomenon and therefore cannot be cured unless it is accompanied by other treatable forms of sleep disorder (such as insomnia or a stressful situation).
However, there are a few things you can do, and here are some precautions:
Make sure the child remains calm before going to bed.
Choose reassuring toys and avoid watching scary or more aggressive TV shows or series.
Children who are prone to nervousness or have difficulty relaxing are taught some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This will help the child to sleep more calmly.
When we start talking while we are asleep, we try to stay calm.
Remember, this is harmless for the child, and the next day they will not remember anything.
Useful Advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be unnecessary because the child is unconscious, but would get out of sleep.
Despite speaking, he actually continues to sleep and rest.
Remember, if the phenomenon is accompanied by severe anxiety several times, it is advisable to consult a specialist or find out what triggers a high degree of anxiety in the child.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), don’t start asking questions to learn anything from him.
It would be unnecessary, because while sleeping, he is not conscious enough to gather his thoughts.
On the other hand, you only hear the speech, but you do not see the dreams associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and the possible conclusions.
Never tell your child that you can ask them about their secrets at night.
Not even a joke.
This caused great anxiety.
So the main thing is not to worry, as it’s just a few minutes of harmless episodes.
