Blood is safe again.
President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate because Héma-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donor companies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people’s confidence, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood supply service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, in February 1994, the Government of Canada, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched an official investigation aimed at finding out the circumstances that led to the tragedy and making suggestions to avoid future similar cases.
While Judge Krever delayed in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committees aimed at designing a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports resulted in the establishment of two blood services in Canada: one for Héma-Québec, which serves Québec, and the other for all other provinces and territories.
“When Héma-Québec started operations in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Québec’s blood supply system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
“But in the years that followed, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we were able to regain people’s confidence.” Decary is proud to declare that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Québec’s population had already trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, does not forget that “confidence is an extremely fragile thing.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, a number of cases have been discovered in Europe where people have been infected by a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its founding in 1998.
“We didn’t know if this disease spread through blood.
Therefore, we relyed on one of the most important recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusive measures. In this case, we were talking about the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain damage, so inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
A few years ago, it was established without any doubt that the disease also spreads through blood.
This case convinced us that it makes sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which can detect the virus itself directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies formed against the virus, on which the previously used tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period from the infection to the detection of the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk of blood donors infecting the blood supply unknowingly and that this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting blood from a person infected with HIV is 12 million per one.
In other words, this means we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with the HIV virus through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can readily accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You can never know what new pathogens will enter the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, gets into the blood by insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly on the brink,” continued Dr. Décary, then stressing that in addition to the emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
With the ageing of the population, the demands also increase.
As anti-cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need replacement of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has an impact on the blood donor population, with only 3% of Québec’s population being eligible for blood donation on the net.
However, any healthy person, at least 18 years of age, who meets the fitness conditions can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of candidates do not accept blood because they are infected with, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is devastating are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
“With this 3% we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It is very rare to run out of stock.
The number of blood donors, on the other hand, must be increased as existing ones get older, because they can no longer donate blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to persuade people to donate blood, but it is even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today’s rushing world, one has barely an hour to go out to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeball tissue and skin tissue, which is almost exclusively used for people with severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages Québec’s only public stem cell bank.
Formerly treated only as medical waste, the umbilical cord can extract blood that is rich in stem cells, thus enabling the treatment of serious diseases (such as leukemia).
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the introduction of the thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood in our bank and we are planning to take more than a thousand new samples each year.
We’ll probably start offering them for organ transplants by the beginning of next year,” said Dr. Décary, who said the umbilical cord blood collection program is very popular today.
“Many mothers are saddened that they don’t have the opportunity to do so” – this is true because Héma-Québec is not able to make this complex and expensive program available in every hospital in Québec.
