Northern aspirations of Charest
The government does not rule out that the elections will begin this year.
Just as the Liberal Party assembly was over, Jean Charest had already traveled to Jean-Talon in Québec yesterday, where the new health minister, Yves Bolduc (left) is fighting to win today’s interim elections.
“Cut back our last great northern border”: this ambitious long-term goal was outlined by Jean Charest at yesterday’s Liberal Party meeting in Levis, Québec. The speech was also enriched with visual elements, while the president sought to focus on the essence.
During his performance, a series of images like "Moulin à images" were projected behind him.
On the three giant projectors, impressive images followed each other: water-power barricades, mining, Quebec on Google Maps, maps...
These tools are used during election periods.
The prime minister, however, refused to guarantee at the press conference that the election would not begin this autumn, although he added that his timetable was very tight.
The "Northern Plan" is the fourth pillar of the Prime Minister's "vision" for the future of Quebec, embodied in a "new economic area", which includes a labor agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and several agreements planned with Ontario.
Recently, opening up to the North (i.e. the northern area starting at 49° latitude) has been frequently included in the Prime Minister’s speeches, but he has never held a lecture on this subject.
The president, however, has only explained why he considers the North a “treasure mine full of tremendous potential”, but has not spoken about the time factor, the amount of investment, or the specific priority order for future projects.
It highlighted only a few development opportunities: water power plants, forestry and, in particular, mining, which is further stimulated by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructures.
There is nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds in the north,” Charest said.
This area, which is "two times the size of France", "is our territory, the territory of Quebec.
It is not only in us, it is in us,” the president repeated, stressing that he intended to create a national founding myth.
He pointed out that the development of Quebec was largely determined by its relationship with the North: the gold fever in Abitibi, the design work in Quebec, the Bay of James...
“This is ours, our future!” he added after taking a stage break and staring at the huge map behind his back.
The north, which covers 70% of Quebec’s territory, includes part of the Labrador, which Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister said at a news conference.
“This is a historic resolution that has been ratified by all governments.
There is a border line on which no agreement has been reached for a long time, and if an opportunity arises, I will reaffirm the same resolution on behalf of the government," he said.
On the other hand, "in light of climate change, we must rethink our view on the North," he said, referring to the northwestern passage that opens every year due to the melting of Arctic ice.
In this new geopolitical environment, the occupation of the territory is an important task.
And what about the indigenous people of the area, the Indians and the Eskimo?
The prime minister said the Quebec government is paying special attention to them and that the plan will benefit them a lot, especially young people.
Two ministers from different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (the latter was a delegate from Parti Québécois in Ungava) have already started consultations with about thirty local communities.
An inter-ministerial committee led by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Minister of Transport and Natural Resources) plays an important role, has also started its work.
The prime minister does not rule out the possibility of a large-scale meeting, "not necessarily a summit" where they "create a common vision".
The development of the North would be carried out in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be coordinated, systematic and at the same time environmentally friendly,” he said.
Jean Charest described this “vision” as consistent with the ideas of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
“Like the former liberals, we think differently: our goal is to create new opportunities for growth and development from challenges.”
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend that began with a large cocktail party on Friday to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage’s election as party chairman.
One of the adopted resolutions proposes that the Beauharnois power plant be renamed Adélard-Godbout.
"The politicians of our party, including Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, Lesage, who implemented the Silent Revolution and the nationwide expansion of hydropower plants, or Bourassa, known as the father of the Bay of James, all knew how to forge the future," Charest said.
At the press conference, he also quoted another, true, conservative work, namely the program "Roads to the North" by John Diefenbaker, the prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Regarding the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydropower barrier plan, President Charest stressed that the commissioning is planned for 2012.
“Let it stay between us, but I plan to be there,” he told his followers, receiving his statement with loud applause.
The prime minister, who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of a vote this fall, which the law allows him.
However, he stressed that the calendar is already full, as he has taken on tasks at the federal council meeting in China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The party assembly held at the end of the week proved to be an excellent platform for the liberal president to express nationalist resolutions, which were approved almost without thought.
They would also like Quebec to be able to appoint members of the Canadian Radio and Telecommunications Council, and these members would have a veto on decisions taken in Quebec.
The opposition, on the other hand, was skeptical of the main points of the Northern Plan.
The leader of the Coastal Québécois, Paulina Marois, resumed the North Québec development policy introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to Marois, the liberal government that came to power in 2003 rejected this policy.
If they had not done so, “we would have gone much further today,” said Marois, in agreement with Ms. Françoise Mercure, who was nominated for the vote in Jean-Talon today.
The ADQ opposition party supports the government’s approval of the Northern Plan.
"But we want it not to be a mere play," said Sébastien Proulx, who replaced Mario Dumont, who has returned from his freedom today.
