Orwell's Speech by Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy president and chief executive of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada, appeared.
Following Orwell’s explanation, Garver claims that the world’s largest gold producer has filed a $6 million defamatory lawsuit against three authors and a small money publishing company in order to initiate a so-called “public debate.”
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decisions – in defamatory cases – are not based on truth but on the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
For Barrick Gold, would it really be the best way for a public debate to destroy anyone whose views are contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada have to spend substantial sums of money defending and fighting in an unequal struggle where on the other side stands an army of lawyers supported by the almost inexhaustible resources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, by the way, they often use the tactic of destroying the defendant and making a friendly settlement, by which they not only silence the opposites, but even frighten those who would try to deal with the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views in front of the public.
While many other countries where Barrick Gold operates do this differently, in Canada, the parties to the dispute usually don’t hit each other with their sticks, but say their thoughts.
It would therefore have been enough for the mine to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in the press, in the media, in publications, paying for independent research teams to shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold has no confidence in the public opinion, and with one move it is shifting aside petitions and letters written to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver explain how he could initiate a “public” debate while ignoring the opinion of this public?
In the vice president’s mind, this word probably only refers to the high-paying lawyers, not the total population of Canada: the meaning of the term is thus much narrowed.
In a democratic country, even those who despise others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand – or does not want to understand – that Noir Canada’s authors and publishers are mostly supported by the public because they condemn the mine’s rude behavior.
The public is willing to listen to Barrick and make a judgment, but it would do so on civilized grounds, rather than by a trial of silence for many. (In connection with the term "public debate," by the way, Barrick Gold has recently written to the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using this term.)
Beyond Garver’s surreal arguments, the Barrick Gold Procedure is an open attack on the freedom of university research and the search for truth, which are the building blocks of every democratic society.
As a whole, the procedure denies the right to cite credible sources, something to argue about the facts and their interpretation, which are the basis of intellectual activities.
If, in a country like Canada, it is only possible to study and discuss subjects under the burden of litigation that do not please the wealthy companies of today’s world, then who will take the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, you could do so according to the scientific standards applied by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have the right to answer.
In our university community, we have been able to deal with disputes, disagreements and conflicts for a long time.
Barrick Gold’s reckless behavior shows that, contrary to what he claims, he is unwilling to conduct an open debate.
This is a loss for both the university world and the institution of Canadian public debate.It is time for governments to implement measures to limit legal proceedings initiated for such abuses.
Wall Street bailout: Republicans and Democrats agree
The Bush administration and Republican and Democratic leaders in Congress finally reached an agreement on the economic bailout, the largest such plan since the Great World Economic Crisis in the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan, aimed at curbing the Wall Street financial crisis, has yet to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Key points of the plan are: greater control of implementation by the MEPs; new mechanisms to ensure reimbursement of allocated public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized due to non-payment; access to the salary of managers of companies receiving aid.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican MP Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes before midnight yesterday after the two-day marathon trial ended.
“We’ve made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a spokesman for the Bush administration.
"We have done everything to save the real economy and the American people from the current crisis that has hit Wall Street," he said.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, there will be enormous shock, chaos and confusion in the everyday lives of Americans," said Republican MP Judd Gregg.
The negotiations have been accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental impact on investors’ mood.
The deal was signed until the opening of the stock market this morning.
The two presidential candidates, who joined the negotiations late, expressed their willingness to reach an agreement, but expressed their disappointment that the situation has worsened until the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed to himself the expansion of the deal with elements such as provisions relating to preserving home ownership or paying executives of state-aided companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take some extraordinary steps because of the irresponsibility of others, it’s not very welcome.
