Psychology of overpricing: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvaluing the goods.
The foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior have been explored by neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York.
According to their study in the journal Science, people don’t want to be inferior in a type of competition like auctioning on eBay, so they prefer to pay too high prices.
The research attempted to map the nervous system pattern of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers took a lottery, the other group took part in a gaming auction while examining the active brain areas of the subjects using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but during the auction game - in which an essential element is the exaggeration of the other party - the under-brain complex called striatum was activated when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price can be explained by avoiding the acute reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told how much the real value of the product was and they placed their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they won out of the game, they would receive another $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received just $15 before the auction, but the members of the group lost that money in the event of a losing auction.
Therefore, the difference between the two groups was only that one of them emphasized the win and the other the loss.
However, proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and the "win" group.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have so far only explained the phenomena at auctions with the joy of victory and the avoidance of risks.
Only neurological imaging has helped solve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and chronic liver disease is the leading cause of death in Hungary.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis here, but only seven thousand are treated because patients often don’t know they’re infected.
The term hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characteristic of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused by them differ.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen, spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (spleen, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should be vaccinated against the A and B viruses and there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After these, yellowness on the skin and the white of the eyes develops, the stool becomes bright, the urine becomes dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from the more severe form of the disease, hepatitis B-caused liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receives medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can also lead to cirrhosis, liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
There are three groups with a higher than average number of cases: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattooers.
There are currently 200 million people in the world infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth consulting a family doctor if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
If the disease is detected in time, it can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus eliminating the infectiousness and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first held in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
