Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brains that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research studies involving academics, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a flashing device to the subject’s left hand, which provided the electric shock.
The researchers asked participants to look closely at two paintings, the painting of the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci's painting of the Lady with hermeline in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would evoke a sort of religious state among the believers, while the Da Vinci image was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and was thought to have a soothing effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive sections while watching either the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics that during the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe” as “careful” and “quiet, filled with peace.”
When viewing a religious-themed picture, they 12 percent less pain than when seeing Leonardo’s work.
