Dungeon flight is imitated by smart car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collisions if not by imitating obstacle sensors in the world of nature?
For example the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, Dongo bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point for how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bio-oriented car robot control system, a robotic mini-car equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to develop a system that eliminates all collisions.
“While flying, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety cover,” explains Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and R&D brand director.
The complex eye of the uterus, which can see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To replicate the function of the complex eye, the engineers turned to the idea of a laser telemetry.
This identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 meters in a 180-degree field before the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid a collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot imitates the movements of the uterus, immediately changing the direction of its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the car robot’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and car robot project.
You must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety cover, a layer within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what one bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process must take place at a glance.
But, unlike bees, the deviation may not be directed upwards, downwards, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the reversibility of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration, as well as slowing, were used here as the option available to the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, let alone the ability to store it.
This structure only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to save them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so you constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or even megabytes of memory are needed.
This is the first step in the development of instantaneous evasion technology, which Nissan estimates could be used in mass-production vehicles within ten years.
An additional application may be to combine the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to drive the car to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
