The elite is in danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion bailout proposed by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which reports that the current crisis has created a crackdown within the Republican Party, which shows a growing divide between the traditional, restrained East Coast attitude that supports federal institutions and business circles and the growing anti-Washington and financial new trend in the central and southern states.
This trend was expressed critically in the voting in the House of Representatives mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is only one of the major changes that the economic restructuring that is still ongoing predicts or makes visible, and not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the United States and in Europe, is only accelerating the phenomena that have long been out of place, which are consolidating in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-actualization, the return of the double category of state sovereignty to the public consciousness, in connection with a sort of re-nationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis affects those banking and financial institutions, which, whileining close ties with the outside world, are primarily, and in a fairly broad way, engaging people and families who live in one country, in one state.
This, in turn, represents a direct political difficulty for those in government: what to respond to the difficulties and protests of those who are also voters.
Thus, although the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
Political internationalism appears to be essentially stranded outside the coastline: the European Union is a strong proof of this, unable to set a unified political orientation in the midst of different interests and different national strategies.
So everyone expects the individual national governments to intervene, the rescue package, the rebound and the new rules, but above all the opening of funds: because in a difficult situation only the individual states have economic resources, a financial reserve that can be able to fix things.
They also have the tools and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that no other market or international organization will possess to such an extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the national state is fully consistent with the fact that the recent economic growth has attributed an increasing importance to one factor that is closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, an increasingly sophisticated technology, and were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we had to realize that our future increasingly depended on abstract things such as water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one half of the planet to the other, yet are entirely bound to a delimited place, a territory.
Thus, the one who controls the territory has far more cards than the one who unfortunately was born in a place where there is no harvest, no oil, and no water.
I would like to go on to the second issue, which is a kind of breakdown line.
Whoever says that it is territory, state, government, necessarily also says: politics, in other words, leadership.
From this perspective, the economic crisis seems to produce two intertwined phenomena:
On the one hand, an objective recognition of the need for authentic leadership, someone who can take the events in hand.
On the other hand, the current leadership brings a total credit loss, especially to economic managers, who have proved completely inadequate and have proved that many are still in the vague field ahead of them.
Together, the two have even deeper significance and in a sense worrisome: the feeling of loss of credit, impatience, inadequacy and separation that affects the entire leadership elite in a growing number of Western countries.
Therefore, it seems that there is a growing belief among the population that the time of the social elite at its peak has ended. It has ended, even before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, cultures, in the complex sense of the word, have been embraced.
In a word, the demand for leadership, in a covert form, feeds a multi-faceted but strong delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is manifested in the unexpected "revolts" of voters or in recent sudden changes in public mood. Such as the rise of conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the workers' unity in Great Britain, or the uprising of U.S. congressional representatives against Bush (and the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, programs, and even with its customs, press, and renowned intellectuals, is becoming less and less understandable, and therefore less and less able to represent what has been happening for a while in the deeper layers of Western society.
Despite all this, speaking of “the imminent revolt of the masses” would be frankly exaggerated.
