Farewell to the old Cinema Paradiso, the time of the old cinemas has been sacrificed in the cities
Traditional cinemas are closed in favor of the Multiplexes.
“A city without a cinema, a blind city, is like a face without eyes.”
Images taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrate what is happening in Italian cities, but also in rural areas.
The expulsion of the cinemas – the emergence of large, multi-room cinemas in the suburbs and, consequently, the extinction of the one-room cinemas in the city centers – is a process that seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time carries all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it's like a friend going away, a friend we've shared our journey with and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which marks twenty years ago the Oscar award and the Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival to Tornator, tells the lyrical story of a small town cinema, the craving, after a movie experience that may have been lost forever.
The largest association of operators, Anec, figures that speak clearly: in the past five years 316 traditional film theaters have closed.The biggest losses have been recorded in the cinemas in major cities: 10 film theaters closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin, and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions is Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that it is precisely the proliferation of the multiplex that is responsible for their disappearance, we do not prove better than that Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years the number of rooms has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and equally in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Paolo Protti, chairman of Anec. "It's okay to build new facilities, but the survival of those already existing should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not every entrance is willing to move to the multiplex.
Not to mention the unpaid financial funds intended to support operators: the state’s outstanding debt can be approximately 10 million euros.
It is also ethically and morally shameful that the government does not comply with the laws in force.
It would require 16 to 18 million euros per year to maintain the market.”
Particular attention is paid to the case of Bologna. This is the first Italian city that, concerned about closures, has decided to resolve the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost the single-room cinemas outside and in the city centre.
The provisions would include tax reductions for operators and benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers would be able to ride into restricted areas and park at a discounted rate in certain parking spaces.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even with the introduction of other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
But it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the domination of the multiplex, need to improve the quality of sound and image, because today’s audience is much more demanding.
Preserving the traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that eventually made me Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I walk on the Via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or Quirinale to avoid the dust-blacked posters, I turn my head.
